John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scotland's independent schools have a long history of excellent academic performance, and this continues in 2018 with a further string of outstanding results, further enhanced by individual and collective success in sport, the arts, music and other community endeavours.
With up to 30,000 pupils around Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to their pupils and parents.
The independent schools try to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a tailored curriculum, we are seeing that modern languages remain a popular subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it hits his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it touches his heart".
It is an important reminder that we cannot just stick to English when we want to build relationships and trust between people from other countries.
We can look at the most recent test results this year, and language is at the top of the statistics with the highest pass rates in the independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of the students who studied foreign languages received high A's.
Data collected by the 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 per cent of pupils obtained A's in Mandarin, while 72 per cent of those studying German, 69 per cent of those studying French and 63 per cent of those studying Spanish also obtained A's.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Language is now being considered as a subject choice on the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent schools and elsewhere.
A study by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 found that 17% of the reasons employers could not fill vacancies were related to a lack of language skills.
Language skills are therefore becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
More jobs in the future will require language skills, and these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Whatever career young people choose, if they have learned another language, they have a great advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a multilingual person an edge over the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov poll of over 4,000 people in the UK, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French is the only language spoken by a multi-digit percentage, 15 percent.
That is why it is important to invest in language education for children today.
Knowing more languages, especially those of developing countries, gives children a better chance of finding meaningful work.
In Scotland, the languages taught differ between schools.
A number of schools focus on the more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are expected to be most important for the UK as we look ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, there will always be a variety of languages to choose from at independent schools with teachers who are specialists in the field.
Scottish Independent Schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds.
At this stage, it cannot be denied that languages continue to be really important for the future of the country in a global business environment, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should really be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, this diversity and this excellence to Scotland's youth.
It's the right thing to do.
John Edward is head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
