North Korea says it won't disarm unilaterally if there's no trust.
North Korea's foreign minister told the UN on Saturday that continued sanctions reinforce their distrust of the United States and that the country would not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the General Assembly of the World Organization that North Korea had shown "significant goodwill" over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, shutting down a nuclear test site and pledging not to develop nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"We have not seen a similar reaction from the United States", he said.
"Without trust in the United States, there is no trust in our national security and under such circumstances, there is no chance that we ourselves will take the first step and disarm unilaterally".
While Ri reiterated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's opposition to a "phased" approach to nuclear disarmament, where North Korea would be rewarded if it took gradual steps, his speech seemed important as it did not unequivocally reject unilateral disarmament, as has been the case in the past from Pyongyang.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between a sitting US president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim promised to work on "nuclear disarmament on the Korean Peninsula", while Trump promised to guarantee North Korea's security.
North Korea has demanded a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also shown resistance to softening tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The US insists on 'nuclear disarmament first' and builds pressure with sanctions to achieve their goals by force and even opposes the 'declaration on the end of the war'", Ri said.
"The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a wishful dream among people who don't know who we are.
But the problem is that the continuation of sanctions reinforces our mistrust".
Ri did not mention plans for another summit between Kim and Trump, which the US leader highlighted at the UN earlier this week.
The minister instead highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months, adding: "If the denuclearisation negotiations were to be with South Korea and not the United States, the negotiations would not be so deadlocked".
Nevertheless, the tone of Rice's speech was very different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea's launch of missiles at the US mainland was inevitable, after "Mr Evil President" Trump called Kim a "rocket man" on a suicide mission.
Last year, Trump threatened at the UN with "total annihilation" of North Korea, but this year he praised Kim for his courageous disarmament efforts, but said that much remains to be done and that sanctions must remain in place until North Korea is quieted down.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no timetable for these actions, but said, "It doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years or five months".
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that: "The Security Council must maintain sanctions with conviction and without error until we achieve total, final, confirmed nuclear disarmament".
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously increased economic sanctions against North Korea in an attempt to halt Pyongyang's missile and nuclear weapons programmes.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for another meeting.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times during the year, but his last trip didn't go well.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying progress had been made, while North Korea accused him of making "gangster-like demands" just hours later.
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea promised to shut down a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States took "corresponding steps".
He said Kim had told him that the "corresponding steps" he demanded were the security promises Trump made in Singapore, as well as moves toward normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on getting enough sleep
A new course at Harvard University has given all undergraduate students more sleep, designed to counter the growing macho culture of studying all night on a high caffeine diet.
One researcher has shown that students at the world's best universities often have no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He got the idea for the course after giving a talk on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
"When the essay was finished, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why don't I know about this until I'm on the exam?'
"She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me", he told The Telegraph.
The course, offered for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleep habits can improve academic and athletic performance and overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health department, says the university decided to offer the course after finding that students were severely sleep deprived during the week.
The one-hour course consists of various interactive exercises.
In one of the exercises, there's a picture of a college room where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, running shoes and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, and how poor sleep affects athletic performance, and the importance of good sleep habits.
In another part of the course, participants learn how prolonged sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, blood clots, depression, and cancer.
Participants are encouraged to reflect on their daily habits by clicking on various icons on an interactive map of the campus.
"We know that it will not change students' behaviour immediately.
But we think they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know how cigarettes affect your health", adds Professor Czeisler.
The pride of an all-nighter still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and increased pressure on students have made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
The "secret weapon" against stress, fatigue, and anxiety is good and adequate sleep, he said. It even prevents weight gain because lack of sleep makes the brain think you're hungry, which is why you're constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped organize the course last year when he took one of Professor Czeisler's courses during his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and made him work on making it a university-wide course.
He hopes that the next step will be to offer all graduates a similar course before continuing their education.
Professor Czeisler recommends setting an alarm to alert students to the harmful effects of electronic screen light, which can slow the circadian rhythm and make it harder to fall asleep.
