Yearbook: The inventor of the Geiger counter
And now a page from the Sunday Morning yearbook: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today  if we count...  was the day that the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger invented a method of detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that would eventually lead to the apparatus known as the Geiger counter.
The Geiger counter has become a staple of both science and popular culture, as seen in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", starring Roy Rogers and Dale Evans as peasant scientists:
Man: "What in the world is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter used to find radioactive minerals like uranium.
When you put these headphones on, you can actually hear the effects of the atoms that the radioactivity in the minerals is making".
Evans: "Stop it, this is it!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name lives on.
New cancer vaccine can teach immune system to "see" cancer cells
New cancer vaccine can teach immune system to "see" cancer cells and kill them
Vaccines teach the immune system to recognize cancer cells as part of treatment
The method involves extracting immune cells from a patient and changing them in the laboratory
They can then "see" the protein that is common to many cancers and where they are injected again.
A trial vaccine shows promise in patients with a number of cancers.
When a woman with ovarian cancer was treated with the vaccine, which teaches the immune system to recognize cancer cells, the cancer disappeared in more than 18 months.
The method involves removing immune cells from patients and changing them in the laboratory to "see" the protein called HER2, which many cancers have, and then injecting the cells back into them.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: "Our results suggest that we have a very promising vaccine".
HER2 "causes several cancers to develop", including breast, ovarian, lung, and bowel cancer, explains Professor Berzofsky.
A similar approach, in which immune cells are taken from patients and "taught" to attack cancer cells, has worked in treating a particular type of leukemia.
