HIV/AIDS: China reports a 14% increase in new cases
China has reported a 14% increase in the number of citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
More than 820,000 people in the country have been affected, according to health officials.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, 40,000 new cases were recorded.
The vast majority of new cases were sexually transmitted, which is a new trend.
Traditionally, HIV spread rapidly in some parts of China through transfusions of infected blood.
But the number of people infected with HIV in this way has been reduced to almost zero, Chinese health officials told a conference in Yunnan province.
In one year, however, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000.
Sexually transmitted HIV is an acute problem in China's LGBT community.
In 1997, homosexuality was legalized, but discrimination against LGBT people is said to be widespread.
Studies estimate that 70-90% of men who have sex with other men eventually marry women because of the country's conservative values.
Many infections are due to a lack of contraception in these conditions.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised free and equal access to HIV medicines in an attempt to address the problem.
