What is the Global Citizens Festival, and has it done anything to reduce poverty?
On Saturday, New York is hosting the Global Citizens Festival , an annual music festival with a very impressive lineup of artists and an equally impressive goal: to end world poverty.
For the seventh time, the Global Citizens Festival will welcome tens of thousands of people to the Central Park lawn to watch concerts by Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, while raising awareness of the ultimate goal of ending extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival was launched in 2012 and is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international advocacy organization that fights to end poverty by increasing the number of active opponents.
To receive a free ticket to the event (if you do not want to pay for a VIP ticket), concertgoers must perform a series of tasks or "actions", such as volunteering, writing to a world leader, making a phone call, or any other meaningful action that can raise awareness of the goal of ending poverty.
But how successful has Global Citizen been, now that they have 12 years left to reach their goal?
Does the idea of rewarding people with a free concert really create change, or is it just another case of so-called clicktivism  i.e. people feeling they are making a difference by signing a petition online or posting on Twitter?
Global Citizen reports that since 2011, it has recorded more than 19 million "actions" by its members directed at various targets.
They believe that these actions have prompted world leaders to make binding targets and policies worth more than $37 billion, which by 2030 are expected to have affected more than 2.25 billion people.
At the beginning of 2018, the group listed 390 targets and actions that had been achieved as a result of their actions, amounting to over $10 billion already paid or raised.
The group estimates that these funds have so far directly affected nearly 649 million people worldwide.
One of the main goals is The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based venture between investors and businesspeople that aims to "help children reach their full potential" and pledges $35 million to address nutritional problems in Rwanda after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
"With the help of the UK government, donors, other governments and citizens like you, the social injustice of malnutrition can become a footnote in the history books", The Power of Nutrition ambassador Tracey Ullman told the audience at a concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that the UK government has now pledged funds to improve nutrition for mothers and children after receiving more than 5,000 online calls.
In response to one of the website's frequently asked questions: "What makes you think we can end extreme poverty?"
Global Citizen wrote: "It's going to be a long and hard fight, and sometimes we're going to stumble and make mistakes.
But as with the civil rights movement and the anti-apartheid movement, it will succeed because we are stronger together".
