The inventor of the Internet plans to create a new Internet to compete with Google and Facebook
The inventor of the Internet, Tim Berners-Lee, is launching a new company to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The tech giant's latest project is called Inrupt, and it's a company that builds on Berners-Lee's open source platform Solid.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and who can access what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners Lee joked that the Inrupt plan is "world domination".
"We have to do it now", he said of the startup business.
"This is a historic moment".
The app uses Solid's technology, allowing people to create their own "personal online data collection" or POD.
It may contain contact lists, to-do lists, calendars, music libraries and other personal and professional tools.
It's as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were all available in a single browser at the same time.
The unique feature of online personal data collection is that it is entirely up to the user to decide who can access the specific information.
The company calls it "personal empowerment through data".
The idea behind Inrupt, according to the company's CEO, John Bruce, is to pool resources, processes and capabilities to make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform acquired by IBM, some software developers on project contracts and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralized apps using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee says that he and his team are not talking to "Facebook or Google about whether they should completely change everything so that all their business models suddenly become redundant".
"We're not asking for their permission".
In a post on Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt's "mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that can ensure the integrity and quality of the new Internet built on Solid".
In 1994, Berners-Lee changed the Internet when he started the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been a major voice in the so-called net neutrality debate.
While Inrupt is launched, Berners-Lee will remain the inventor and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I am incredibly optimistic about the next period of the Internet", Berners-Lee added.
