Mickelson on the bench for the Ryder Cup on Saturday.
American Phil Mickelson will set a new record on Sunday when he plays his 47th Ryder Cup match, but he's got to do something about his form if he doesn't want to be a sad milestone.
Mickelson, who is the record holder for the 12th time in the competition, which is held every two years, was benched by Captain Jim Furyk for Saturday's fourballs and foursomes.
Instead of being in the center of the American scene as usual, the five-time major winner had to cheer and practice his game in the hope of correcting the mistakes.
Even at the height of his career, he had the most straight drive, which is why the 48-year-old is not a perfect match for the course at Le Golf National, where the long rough often penalizes stray shots.
