Germany's new warship is being delayed again
The German Navy's newest frigate was due to be ready in 2014 to replace Cold War warships, but the Germans have to wait at least another year due to technical problems and an escalating price tag, local media reports.
The commissioning of the largest ship in the all-new Baden-Wuerttemberg class of frigates, the "Rheinland-Pfalz", has been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, citing a military spokesman.
The ship was due to join the fleet in 2014, but backlog problems have plagued the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships ordered by the Navy back in 2007 are to replace the ageing Bremen-class frigates.
They are known to have a powerful cannon, a large variety of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as stealth technologies such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Another important feature of the newest frigates is a reduced maintenance requirement: it should be possible to keep the frigates away from home ports for up to two years.
But the repeated delays mean that the advanced warships  that are supposed to make Germany appear as an overseas power  will already be obsolete when deployed, reports Die Zeit.
The failed F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to take the ship into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to the shipbuilder after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but German media reported a number of crucial "software and hardware flaws" that rendered the warship unusable in combat situations.
Software errors were of particular importance, as the Baden-Wuerttemberg class ships are to be manned by a crew of 120 sailors, only half the crew of the older Bremen frigates.
It also proved to be too heavy, reducing its performance and limiting the fleet's ability to make future upgrades.
The 7,000-ton "Rheinland-Pfalz" is said to be twice as heavy as similar ships used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to hardware failures, the cost of the project, which includes training the crew, is also becoming a problem.
It is said to have reached a staggering €3.1 billion ($3.6 billion), with an original price tag of €2.2 billion.
The problems with the latest frigates are becoming even more important in light of recent warnings that Germany's naval power is shrinking.
Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German government's defence committee, admitted earlier this year that the fleet was "running out of ready-to-go ships".
The official said that the problem has grown over time because the old ships were taken out of service without being replaced.
He complained that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class frigates were ready to join the fleet.
The National Trust is eavesdropping on the secret lives of bats
New research from an area in the Scottish Highlands is trying to uncover how bats use the landscape when hunting.
The hope is that the findings will shed light on the unique behaviour of flying mammals and will help in future conservation efforts.
The study, carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, follows bats, bats, bats and water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed at carefully selected locations in the area to record the bat's activities throughout the season.
Data are also collected by NTS staff and volunteers using handheld detectors.
In-depth analysis of the audio recordings will reveal the frequencies of the bat calls and show which species is doing what.
To produce a detailed landscape picture of their behavior, a report and a map of the habitat are made.
NTS conservation adviser Rob Dewar hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important and how they are used by the different species.
This knowledge can help to determine the benefits of habitat conservation measures such as the establishment of meadows and how best to preserve forest areas for bats and similar species.
The number of bats in Scotland and Britain has fallen dramatically over the past 100 years.
They are threatened by buildings and urban development projects that affect the herders and restrict their habitat.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a danger, as can fly traps, chemical treatment of building materials, and attacks by pets.
Bat mice are not actually blind.
But because they hunt primarily at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes.
They use advanced echolocation technology to locate insects and fly around obstacles.
The NTS, which is responsible for the preservation of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens, and 76,000 acres of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten trained experts who often gather data, inspect nests, and sometimes perform rescue operations.
The organisation has even created Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve in the area around Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight out of ten of Scotland's bat species.
The area's warden, David Thompson, says it's an ideal territory for them.
"Here at Threave we have a really good bat area", he said.
"We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all the good habitat.
There is much that is unknown about bats, so working here and elsewhere can help you to understand what they need to thrive".
He stresses the importance of looking for bats before doing any maintenance on property, since the destruction of a single nest can kill up to 400 females and young, risking the extinction of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, disturb or disturb them or their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish project manager for the Bat Conservation Trust, has called on the public to lend a hand.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species we have, we don't know how populations evolve".
