Here are some facts about Palu and Donggala, on the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of Central Sulawesi Province and is located at the bottom of a narrow bay on the west coast of Sulawesi Island, which in 2017 had an estimated population of 379,800.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami hit.
Donggala is a regency that stretches over more than 300 km of coastline on the northwestern part of Sulawesi Island.
The Regency, which is an administrative region under a province, had an estimated population of 299,200 in 2017.
Fisheries and agriculture are the mainstays of the Central Slavic economy, especially in the coastal area of Donggala.
Nickel mining is also important in the province, but mainly takes place in Morowali, which is the coast opposite Sulawesi.
According to the Indonesian Disaster Center, Palu and Donggala have been hit by tsunamis several times in the past 100 years.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
In 1996, Donggala was again hit by a tsunami that killed nine.
Indonesia is located on the Pacific Rim and is regularly struck by earthquakes.
Some of the largest earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years have been:
2004: A powerful earthquake on the west coast of Indonesia's Aceh province in northern Sumatra triggered a tsunami on December 26, which struck 14 countries and killed 226,000 people along the Indian Ocean coastline, including more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds died on the island of Nias off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 earthquake struck south of Java, Indonesia's most populous island, triggering a tsunami that swept the southern coast and killed nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6-magnitude earthquake struck near the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra Province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude earthquake hits one of the Mentawai Islands off Sumatra, triggering a 10-meter-high tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A shallow earthquake hit the Pidie Jaya regency in Aceh, spreading destruction and panic as people were reminded of the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
No tsunami was triggered this time, but more than 100 were killed by the collapsing buildings.
2018: A powerful earthquake struck Indonesia's tourist island of Lombok, killing more than 500 people, mostly on the north side of the island.
The earthquake destroyed thousands of buildings and temporarily stranded thousands of tourists.
